package. Let me now look at:\n1. The main task-hall.ps1 script to understand how commands are implemented\n2. Any heartbeat patterns in the codebase\n3. The agent-cli mapping config to see how agents are invoked\n4. The common/cli.ps1 to understand how packages are loaded\n\nLet me also search for any \"heartbeat\" patterns in the codebase.\n\n\nLet me also check for heartbeat patterns and the agent-workflow package to get a complete picture.\n\n\nNo heartbeat found in capability-library. Let me search for \"alive\", \"ping\", \"check\", \"monitor\" or similar patterns related to task-hall or agent processes. Also check the state/listings.json to see the data structure.\n\n\nNow I have a thorough understanding of the task-hall package. Let me also check the agent-cli package for the task-hall-frontdesk agent reference, and see if there's anything related to heartbeat/liveness in the codebase.\n\n\nThe `mount` command is exactly what I was looking for with \"heartbeat\" - it says \"Keep an agent session alive with scheduled lifecycle heartbeats\". Let me read the agent-cli script to understand the mount/heartbeat pattern.\n\n\nGrep is not available. Let me read the agent-cli script directly.\n\n\nI found the `mount` command in agent-cli. Let me search for the specific heartbeat-related code in agent-cli.ps1. Let me read more of the file to find the mount-related functions.\n\n\nThe grep tool is not working. Let me use the read tool to look at more of the agent-cli.ps1 file to find mount/heartbeat-related code.\n\n\nNow I have a good understanding. Let me compile the findings.\n\n\n<results>\n<files>\n- `D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\mycli\\task-hall\\cli.package.json` - task-hall command registry (16 commands: init, submit-request, upload, upload-publish, publish, tasks, show, edit, claim, release, submit, review-submission, done, cancel, delete, archive)\n- `D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\mycli\\task-hall\\scripts\\task-hall.ps1` - 995-line PowerShell implementation of all task-hall commands\n- `D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\mycli\\task-hall\\README.md` - full protocol documentation (frontdesk-v0.2, reviewer-v0.1, status model, storage structure, agent usage norms)\n- `D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\mycli\\task-hall\\state\\listings.json` - current task listings index (5 tasks: 3 done, 2 draft)\n- `D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\mycli\\task-hall\\state\\events.jsonl` - append-only event log (73 events covering full task lifecycle)\n- `D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\mycli\\task-hall\\state\\tasks\\` - per-task directories with `task.md`, `meta.json`, `claims.jsonl`, `submissions.jsonl`, review artifacts\n- `D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\mycli\\agent-cli\\cli.package.json` - agent-cli registry; includes `mount` command for \"scheduled lifecycle heartbeats\"\n- `D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\mycli\\agent-cli\\scripts\\agent-cli.ps1` - contains `Invoke-MountHeartbeat` (lines ~2085-2146) and `Get-HeartbeatPrompt` (lines ~2053-2071) — the heartbeat pattern\n- `D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\mycli\\common\\cli.ps1` - generic mycli runtime (package/command registration, dispatch)\n</files>\n\n<answer>\n## task-hall Command Architecture\n\n**Command definitions** live in `cli.package.json` (16 commands) and are implemented in `task-hall.ps1`. The mycli runtime (`common/cli.ps1`) dispatches to the entry script with `prefixArgs`.\n\n### Task Lifecycle (claim/review)\n\n1. **submit-request** → calls `agent-cli run --agent opencode/task-hall-frontdesk` to validate JSON and auto-generate `task.md` with `## 领取门槛` section\n2. **claim** → calls frontdesk agent to vet `model_tier` against task's minimum requirement; writes `claim-review-{timestamp}.json`\n3. **review-submission** → calls `opencode/task-hall-reviewer` with original task Markdown + agent's report Markdown; reviewer returns `complete|return_to_agent|relist_as_is|revise_and_relist`\n\n**Status model**: `draft → listed → claimed → done` (or `cancelled/archived`)\n\n### Heartbeat Pattern\n\nThe **existing heartbeat/check pattern** is in `agent-cli` under `mount`:\n- **Entry**: `mycli agent-cli mount add --agent <name> [--session <id>] [--interval_minutes <n>]`\n- **Mechanism**: Windows Task Scheduler triggers `agent-cli.ps1 mount tick <mount-id>` on a fixed interval\n- **Heartbeat logic** (`Invoke-MountHeartbeat`, lines ~2085-2146):\n  - Skips if a future schedule exists for the session\n  - Skips if agent worked within `quiet_minutes` (default 30 min)\n  - Otherwise fires a lightweight agent prompt: \"You are being woken by agent-cli mount heartbeat...\"\n  - Tracks `last_tick_utc`, `last_action`, `generation` counter\n  - If response contains `AGENT_CLI_LIFECYCLE_END` marker, increments generation and clears session (fresh session next tick)\n- **State stored**: `D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\mycli\\agent-cli\\state\\mounts\\{mount_id}.json`\n\n**No task-hall-specific heartbeat exists** — task-hall is a passive registry. The only \"liveness\" pattern is the `agent-cli mount` heartbeat infrastructure above.\n</answer>\n\n<next_steps>\nIf you need a task-hall heartbeat (e.g., auto-expire stale claimed tasks, poll for stuck tasks), the pattern to follow is `agent-cli mount`'s `Invoke-MountHeartbeat` approach: a PowerShell function that checks state files, optionally fires an agent prompt, and updates status metadata. You would add a new `mycli task-hall heartbeat` command in `cli.package.json` pointing to `task-hall.ps1` with a `heartbeat` subcommand implemented via `Invoke-TaskHallHeartbeat` following the same `state/listings.json` + `state/events.jsonl` pattern.\n</next_steps>\n</results>","metadata":{"truncated":false,"task_id":"bg_6f26d5f6","agent":"explore","category":"","description":"Explore task hall package","sessionId":"ses_23e3eab70ffeajZUC6sPx73v9H"},"title":"explore - Explore task hall package","time":{"start":1777072240903,"end"